  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Feasibility study for the recycling of plastic waste</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Plastic waste is a major environmental hazard in urban areas of many developing countries, particularly in Nigeria where plastic sachets are widely used for drinking water. The waste clogs drains and causes flash flooding which creates health hazards. However, the waste is also a resource that can through recycling create employment and improve living conditions. The aim of this project is to carry out a feasibility study to inform the establishment of a demonstration recycling plant which can subsequently be replicated in other communities suffering similar challenges. The feasibility study will: investigate the nature and availability of waste plastic; evaluate existing, and generate new, product ideas; understand existing supply chains and potential market niches; assess the economics and logistics of establishing recycling plants; and identify potential business models for the establishment and roll out of recycling plants. This research will lead to a sustainable business model for the safe collection, handling and recycling of waste into affordable building materials, household products and a timber replacement material. This will in turn create employment and improve the environment and well being of poor communities.</narrative>
  </description>
